findings.recommendation:
Add the missing two regex guards exactly as recommended in round-1:
```kotlin
private val MODEL_FILE_REGEX = Regex("^[A-Za-z0-9._-]+$")
private val COMMIT_HASH_REGEX = Regex("^[0-9a-f]{40}$")
// inside the for-loop:
require(MODEL_FILE_REGEX.matches(m.modelFile)) { "modelFile fails schema: ${m.modelFile}" }
require(COMMIT_HASH_REGEX.matches(m.commitHash)) { "commitHash must be 40-char hex: ${m.commitHash}" }
```
Add a regression test mirroring `parse_rejectsDisallowedModelIdPrefix` for each new guard (e.g., `parse_rejectsTraversalInModelFile`, `parse_rejectsNonHexCommitHash`).

Tighten the regex to forbid pure dot-segment trailing tokens:
```kotlin
private val MODEL_ID_REGEX = Regex("^litert-community/(?![.]+$)[A-Za-z0-9._-]+$")
```
The negative lookahead `(?![.]+$)` rejects any trailing segment that is one or more dots followed by end-of-string. Add a regression test:
```kotlin
@Test fun parse_rejectsDotSegmentModelId() {
  for (id in listOf("litert-community/.", "litert-community/..", "litert-community/...")) {
    val json = """{"models":[{"name":"x","modelId":"$id","modelFile":"a.lm",
      "commitHash":"abc","sizeInBytes":1,"taskTypes":["llm_chat"]}]}"""
    assertTrue("must reject $id", parseRaw(json).isFailure)
  }
}
```
